{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487123"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:58:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:58:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"258"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/258"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.66,0.04,0.13,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"258"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82085"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/258"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"258"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67292"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"288"},{"type":"tags","id":"1095"},{"type":"tags","id":"1154"},{"type":"tags","id":"1818"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28"},{"type":"contributions","id":"309"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43789"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82085"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-week history of joint pain in her ankles and elbows, associated with bilateral eye pain and redness. She reports a six-month history of abdominal pain with intermittent bloody diarrhoea, and weight loss of eight kilograms. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works in an office and smokes five cigarettes per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft, with tenderness in the right iliac fossa. There is bilateral and symmetrical swelling of her ankle and elbow joints, with restricted range of movement due to pain. There are no overlying skin changes. Multiple erythematous, tender nodules are present over her shins bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her joint pain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Viral polyarthralgia","Enteropathic arthritis","Psoriatic arthritis","Systemic lupus erythematosus","Reactive arthritis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) with extra-intestinal manifestations. \u003Cstrong\u003EEnteropathic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in up to 30% of patients with IBD and typically affects large joints in a symmetrical pattern, as seen in this case. The combination of chronic bloody diarrhoea, weight loss, and constitutional symptoms strongly supports an underlying diagnosis of IBD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral polyarthralgia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute onset joint pain, often following a viral prodrome with fever, malaise, and myalgia. The chronic gastrointestinal symptoms and extra-intestinal manifestations would be highly unusual for a viral cause. Viral arthralgia is usually self-limiting within weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriatic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with peripheral arthritis but would typically be associated with psoriatic skin lesions such as silvery plaques on extensor surfaces or nail changes. The gastrointestinal symptoms and erythema nodosum would be unusual. While psoriatic arthritis can be asymmetric or symmetric, it commonly affects the distal interphalangeal joints.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause arthritis but would not explain the chronic gastrointestinal symptoms. Additional features such as malar rash, photosensitivity, or serositis would be expected. The arthritis in SLE tends to be migratory and non-erosive, often affecting the small joints of the hands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReactive arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E can occur following gastrointestinal infections such as \u003Cem\u003ECampylobacter jejuni \u003C/em\u003Eor \u003Cem\u003EShigella\u003C/em\u003E, but the prolonged six-month history of symptoms would be unusual, as reactive arthritis typically develops within weeks of the initial infection and is self-limiting. It classically presents with the triad of arthritis, urethritis, and conjunctivitis, which differs from this presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of anterior uveitis (eye pain and redness) and erythema nodosum (painful shin nodules) are well-recognised extra-intestinal manifestations of IBD, further supporting the diagnosis of enteropathic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Enteropathic arthritis occurs in up to 30% of patients with inflammatory bowel disease and typically affects large joints symmetrically.","Extra-intestinal manifestations of inflammatory bowel disease include anterior uveitis and erythema nodosum.","The combination of chronic diarrhoea, weight loss, and arthritis should prompt consideration of inflammatory bowel disease."],"references":["Peluso R, Di Minno MN, Iervolino S, Manguso F, Tramontano G, Ambrosino P, Esposito C, Scalera A, Castiglione F, Scarpa R. Enteropathic spondyloarthritis: from diagnosis to treatment. Clin Dev Immunol. 2013; 2013:631408","Oxford Handbook of Clinical Medicine. 10th Edition. Chapter 12: Rheumatology. 201. p550-555","Barkhodari A, Lee KE, Shen M, Shen B, Yao Q. Inflammatory Bowel Disease: Focus on Enteropathic Arthritis and Therapy. Rheumatol Immunol Res. 2022;3(2):69-76. Published 2022 Jul 6. doi:10.2478/rir-2022-0012"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67292"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"258"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67292"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T21:04:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-27T21:11:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"258"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82085"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,